I added a function called `callme` in `Coin.js` in the platformer example, and then added this in level.js

```
var node = self.scene.createChildPrefab("Coin", "Prefabs/Coin.prefab");
var script=node.getJSComponent("Coin");
script.callme();
```

This fails with a message that `callme` is undefined.

Looked through the code, looks like when a prefab is loaded `JSComponent::InitInstance` is called only in `JSComponent::Update`, so the instance isn't initialized immediately after `createChildPrefab`

If an [Inspector] attributed field type is an enum from an assembly other than the one a component is defined in (eg AtomicNET.dll), its IsEnum is not set and so it cannot be mapped and used in the inspector. 

Eg, the following will result in an Error log ("Component class Foo contains unmappable type TextureUnit in field textureUnit") and will not expose textureUnit in the editor: 

```
public class Foo : CSComponent
{
    [Inspector]
    TextureUnit textureUnit = TextureUnit.TU_DIFFUSE;
}
```

I propose an optional attribute on the component class itself that allows an array of field names to be specified for exclusion:

```
public class ParentComponent : CSComponent
{
    [InspectorField]
    private int superVal1 = 0;
    [InspectorField]
    private int superVal2 = 0;
    [InspectorField]
    private int superVal3 = 0;
}

[RemoveInspectorFields(new [] {"superVal1", "superVal3"})]
public class ChildComponent : ParentComponent
{
    [InspectorField]
    private int childVal = 0;
}

```

This exclusion should be able to be applied in CSComponentInfo.CSComponentInfo:

```
RemoveInspectorFieldsAttribute removeAttr = type.GetCustomAttribute<RemoveInspectorFieldsAttribute>();
string[] excludes = (removeAttr == null) ? new string[] { } : removeAttr.FieldNames;

var fields = type.GetFields(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.NonPublic | BindingFlags.Instance)
.Where(field => {
    return field.IsDefined(typeof(InspectorAttribute), true) &&
           !excludes.Contains(field.Name); 
    });

```

In C++, there is support for accessor-based inspector attributes using the ACCESSOR_ATTRIBUTE macro. Being able to similarly attribute C# properties would allow derived values, as well as validation of values (throwing an exception to disallow setting a value):

```
[Inspector]
public float Angle
{
    get
    {
        return angle;
    }
    set
    {
        if (value <= -360 || angle => 360)
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Angle must be in the range (-360, 360)");

        angle = value;
    }
}
private float angle = 0;
```
